    "post_title": "Blame Short-term Focus for Facebook’s Fall",
    "post_link": "https://www.billgeorge.org/articles/blame-short-term-focus-for-facebooks-fall/",
    "post_date": "August 18, 2012",
    "post_content": [
      "<p>Mark Reilly<br>Managing Editor-&nbsp;<em>Minneapolis / St. Paul Business Journal</em></p><br><em>Minneapolis / St. Paul Business Journal</em><p>Facebook and its social-media cousins could have avoided the public-markets minefield they walked into — and saved investors billions of dollars in losses — had they focused more on building their businesses and less on blasting through IPO records, says former Medtronic Inc. CEO Bill George.</p><p>George, who after leaving Fridley-based Medtronic has become a professor of management practice at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/profiles/company/us/ma/boston/harvard_business_school/977533/\">Harvard Business School</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/08/03/the-long-term-value-of-internet-companies/\">offers his take on the Facebook IPO debacle</a>&nbsp;— and what he calls a second technology bubble — in a post on&nbsp;<em>The New York Times</em>&nbsp;DealBook blog.</p><a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/profiles/company/us/ma/boston/harvard_business_school/977533/\">Harvard Business School</a><a href=\"http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/08/03/the-long-term-value-of-internet-companies/\">offers his take on the Facebook IPO debacle</a><em>The New York Times</em><p>Facebook — as you surely know if you were unfortunate enough to buy in at its IPO price of $38, had a big drop again Thursday&nbsp;<a href=\"http://professional.wsj.com/article/SB10000872396390444375104577593711737087098.html?mod=WSJPRO_hpp_MIDDLETopStories\">as insiders sold off shares</a>. It’s now trading below $20. (Other recent IPOs, like Zynga and Groupon, are also way down).</p><a href=\"http://professional.wsj.com/article/SB10000872396390444375104577593711737087098.html?mod=WSJPRO_hpp_MIDDLETopStories\">as insiders sold off shares</a><p>But, George notes, the social media site is still growing in all its core metrics: new users, ad revenue and income.</p><p>“In a prudent financing environment, investors would be banking on Facebook’s future instead of wondering why it had lost so much of its I.P.O. value,” he writes.</p><p>So what’s the problem? Short-term Wall Street thinking, he argues, which encourages outsized thinking and provokes volatility. George argues that entrepreneurs looking to build for a long-term should stay away from the market until they build “diverse and stable revenue streams.”</p>"
    ]
